      <title>Re: What's the point with mobs that don't show up on ranger tracking?</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Veterans&amp;message.id=217149#M217149</link>
      <description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;We all need to leave out the stuff about &amp;quot;does your target leave tracks, if not you should not be able to track it&amp;quot;. Tracking in Everquest is a class beneficial ability. That is all it is, nothing more. It is like having to get a rogue to open a door with no key. The fact that the door is there and requires it to be picked means you must have a rogue to normally gain access to that content. Everquest is full of class beneficial abilities like this. Want an experience rez from a death? You need a cleric, necromancer, or paladin. Want to charm a specific NPC? You need an enchanter or bard or druid (if it is an animal).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;That being said, the reason to have track it solely because you want to know if an NPC that is desireable for what ever reason is available without having to go directly to the spawn location. No one cares if a moss snake is up or not. But they would care if that randomly spawning highly sought after NPC that is part of their class's epic 1.5 task is up for them. Unfortunately, it is not the moss snake type NPCs that is immune to track, but that NPC used in the epic 1.5 quests.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Do you realize that more half of the NPCs used in all of the classes 1.5 epic quests are immune to track? It is true. What about that group you got together that desides they want to work for that Cloak of the Spirit Tracker quest but have to compete with 3 other groups for it? These are the NPCs that are being tagged as immune to tracking. Making them immune is the equivalent as saying that if a specific NPC kills a character, they cannot be rezed by a cleric. Or a specific locked door cannot be accessed by a rogue with max skills.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;While there may be some small cases where specific content in the game may be enhanced with the addition of non-trackable NPCs, can we really be suggestion that NPCs like those used in the epic 1.5, the ones for the Arcstone Mark tasks, or the Ritesmaster Velok in Ruin of Illisan are truly needing to be immune to track? And guys, it is getting worse with each expansion. Back with Luclin, the number of NPCs that were immune could be counted on one hand. With each expansion, the number grows and does so not in a consent amount either. It is something more then an &amp;quot;accident&amp;quot; in coding can truly be explained. I have yet to find any &amp;quot;an_random_common_NPC_type&amp;quot; that has ever been flagged as immune to tracking.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;-Wadin Pureheart of Quellious&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Plainswalker&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;</description>
