      <title>Re: What's the point with mobs that don't show up on ranger tracking?</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Veterans&amp;message.id=217155#M217155</link>
      <description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;hr&gt;Wadin wrote:&lt;br&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;We all need to leave out the stuff about &amp;quot;does your target leave tracks, if not you should not be able to track it&amp;quot;. Tracking in Everquest is a class beneficial ability. That is all it is, nothing more. It is like having to get a rogue to open a door with no key. The fact that the door is there and requires it to be picked means you must have a rogue to normally gain access to that content. Everquest is full of class beneficial abilities like this. Want an experience rez from a death? You need a cleric, necromancer, or paladin. Want to charm a specific NPC? You need an enchanter or bard or druid (if it is an animal).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;That being said, the reason to have track it solely because you want to know if an NPC that is desireable for what ever reason is available without having to go directly to the spawn location. No one cares if a moss snake is up or not. But they would care if that randomly spawning highly sought after NPC that is part of their class's epic 1.5 task is up for them. Unfortunately, it is not the moss snake type NPCs that is immune to track, but that NPC used in the epic 1.5 quests.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Do you realize that more half of the NPCs used in all of the classes 1.5 epic quests are immune to track? It is true. What about that group you got together that desides they want to work for that Cloak of the Spirit Tracker quest but have to compete with 3 other groups for it? These are the NPCs that are being tagged as immune to tracking. Making them immune is the equivalent as saying that if a specific NPC kills a character, they cannot be rezed by a cleric. &lt;strong&gt;Or a specific locked door cannot be accessed by a rogue with max skills.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;There are locks such as this in game. Not that you said there wasn't exactly, but in case you were unware I figured I'd let you know.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Also, with you first statement *&lt;em&gt;We all need to leave out the stuff about &amp;quot;does your target leave tracks, if not you should not be able to track it&amp;quot;.&lt;/em&gt; * I disagree with completely. If the mobs doesn't leave tracks, how are you tracking it? Yea it's a benificial ability, but look at your other examples: Lots of doors have keys, rogues simply make the access easier (there are exceptions). Some doors have keys and cannot be picked by a rogue with max skill. Charm has a chance of failing for all charm classes, does it not? Just because it's benificial doesn't mean it should work 100% of the time or be completely illogical. Some people prefer at least an ounce of somewhat believable and logical content in their games. Tracking should be just that, tracking. Not magically point me at the mob because the server knows where it is skill. Like it or not, everquest is a roleplaying game. You don't have to even acknoweldge if you don't want. You can instead play the game as though it is a first person shooter with swords, but the game itself will still be (at least somewhat) a role playing game at is base. Those roles should, therefore, make sense.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
