      <title>Re: What's the point with mobs that don't show up on ranger tracking?</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Veterans&amp;message.id=218130#M218130</link>
      <description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;p&gt;Dangon-Veeshan wrote:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;There are locks such as this in game. Not that you said there wasn't exactly, but in case you were unware I figured I'd let you know.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Also, with you first statement *&lt;em&gt;We all need to leave out the stuff about &amp;quot;does your target leave tracks, if not you should not be able to track it&amp;quot;.&lt;/em&gt; * I disagree with completely. If the mobs doesn't leave tracks, how are you tracking it? Yea it's a benificial ability, but look at your other examples: Lots of doors have keys, rogues simply make the access easier (there are exceptions). Some doors have keys and cannot be picked by a rogue with max skill. Charm has a chance of failing for all charm classes, does it not? Just because it's benificial doesn't mean it should work 100% of the time or be completely illogical. Some people prefer at least an ounce of somewhat believable and logical content in their games. Tracking should be just that, tracking. Not magically point me at the mob because the server knows where it is skill. Like it or not, everquest is a roleplaying game. You don't have to even acknoweldge if you don't want. You can instead play the game as though it is a first person shooter with swords, but the game itself will still be (at least somewhat) a role playing game at is base. Those roles should, therefore, make sense.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Statement 1:&lt;/strong&gt;  Yes, I am aware that there are doors that cannot be opened by a max skilled rogue, and that there are NPCs that cannot be charmed by a skilled high level enchanter. For each classes and their set of abilities, there is always some counter to those abilities and classes. That is the way it should be. But the majority of those counters, have a logical reason behind them. Given each door that cannot be picked by a rogue, you most likely find that the specific content behind that door is designed with that in mind, i.e. must complete a specific set of tasks in order for the door to open. Furthermore, I am not suggesting that there should not be content that &lt;strong&gt;IS &lt;/strong&gt;immune to track. That make an specific NPC non-trackable can enhance that content. The Kess events is a successful prime example of such, IMO.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;What I am suggesting though is that all the NPCs that I have personally found to be non-trackable has no reason for it. All of them are what would be consider a &amp;quot;named&amp;quot; NPC (e.g Ritesmaster Vekor in Ruins of Illisan). &lt;strong&gt;NONE &lt;/strong&gt;of them are what would be consider a &amp;quot;common&amp;quot; NPC (e.g. a moss snake). If many of the non-trackable NPCs presently in the game are an &amp;quot;accident&amp;quot;, would not probability state that it is more likely that the number be somewhat evenly distributed between &amp;quot;named&amp;quot; and &amp;quot;common&amp;quot; NPCs, rather then all skewed to &amp;quot;named&amp;quot; NPCs?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Granted, I know that there are some developers that say this is an &amp;quot;accident&amp;quot;, but I will point out that this issue is not a couple weeks or months old, but rather just about 4 years old. And it is an &amp;quot;accident&amp;quot; that has been purpetuated with every expansion even with the multitude of /bug reports. It is also something that I believe has been stated by other developers as being the way it should be. So give me a break if I do not believe the &amp;quot;accident and we will change&amp;quot; it line until I see the results.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Can anyone explain what the rational would be for the 4 named NPCs in Arcstone that are a part of the Mark task that gives the Cloak of the Spirit Tracker be flagged as non-trackable? That is 4 occurances of the &amp;quot;accident&amp;quot; in tagging that seems to be a little to coinencidental. What about the Ritesmaster Velkor in Ruins of Illisan? There is an NPC that is not to far from the zone in, but cannot be detected by a ranger. Instead it needs rogues or monks to scout if it is up. The fact that it cannot be seen on track does not, from anything I have experienced, enhance the content of the event. Tracking has nothing to do with the event. It is spawn location is static. It does not move from its spawn location. It is not overly far from the zone in point. Yet, it is flagged as non-trackable? These are all examples of the current state of the game. They are not made up, but are personal true experiences as seen by this poster.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Statement 2: &lt;/strong&gt;The reason I state to leave the stuff of attempting to justify gaming content and abilities with real life techniques is that it is an impossible and slipperly slope for anyone to use to win. If you make a statement, any statement, that attempts to point to rel life techniques as a reason it should or should not exist, you then open the door for everyone else to do the same. Dangon, you have already seen it and they justly had the right of it with the rogue &amp;quot;Slip into Shadows&amp;quot; argument versus ranger tracking.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Secondly, such arguments violate the first primary rule of all games (and all theatrical movies, btw). That rule being the &lt;em&gt;Suspension of Disbelief&lt;/em&gt;. Wikipedia, free encylopedia defines the &lt;em&gt;Suspension of Disbelief&lt;/em&gt; as &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;a willingness of a reader or viewer to suspend his or her critical faculties to the extent of ignoring minor inconsistencies so as to enjoy a work of fiction&amp;quot;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;"&lt;/em&gt;Video games often require suspension of disbelief. Often, realism is compromised even in games set out to be realistic either intentionally to not overcomplicate game mechanics or due to technical limitations. For example, gunshot wounds are rarely disabling. Some games based on Spider-Man have the comic hero swinging around a city with his webs sticking to nothing but the sky. Another frequent occurrence in games is instant death upon falling into water (instead of giving the player a chance to swim out before drowning)...Role playing games such as Dungeons &amp;amp; Dragons ask the players to use suspension of disbelief when deciding what actions their characters should take. For example, if the players know their Game Master has a history of putting booby traps on the more obvious solutions to obstacles they encounter, a player may have his character press the button labeled &amp;quot;Press me&amp;quot; even though he knows something bad will probably happen, because &amp;quot;it's what the character would do.&amp;quot;&amp;quot; - from en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Suspension_of_disbelief&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;In order for many of these mechanics of this game to work, we must suspend our disbelief. If we do not, we end up with a game that is not really that fun. That is why I say we need to &amp;quot;leave all that stuff&amp;quot; about realizism out of this. It is a losing argument to bring in to the game.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;-Wadin Pureheart of Quellious&lt;br&gt;Plainswalker&lt;/p&gt;</description>
